{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_knarl_ver02/data/sn85040245/00414215440/1913121901/0297.xml":{"full_text":"DIGEST OF WORLD\u2019S\nIMPORTANT NEWS\nEfiTOME OF THE BIG HAPPEN\nINGS OF THE WEEK.\nTO BE READ AT A GLANCE\nItems, Both Foreign and Domestio,\nThat Have Interest for Busy Read\ners, Arranged and Classified\nfor Their Convenience.\nWashington\nAndrew Carnegie takes little stock\nin rumors of business depression,\neither present or impending. At the\nWhite House in Washington _ when\nasked what he thought o? tho general\nbusiness outlook, Mr. Carnegie said:\n\u201cThe recent reports of impending\nwidespread business depression are\nell tonimyrot.\u201d\n\nTne administration currency bill\nwas subjected to many attacks dur\ning the debate in the senate at Wash\nington.\n\nA sweeping investigation of transit\nrates on live stock over railroads in\nwestern classification territory was\nordered by the interstate commerce\ncommission at Washington.\n\nMountain Laurel is proposed as the\nofficial national flower of the United\nSlates in a bill introduced in the\nhouse at Washington by Representa\ntive Kinkead of New York.\n\nPresident Wilson has taken more\ncold and canceled all his engagements\nby order of his physician. Chief Jus\ntice White and Justice Lurton also are\nconfined to their homes In Washington\nsuffering with colds.\n\nThe house at Washington was turned\nInto a circus for an hour and a half.\nRepresentatives Hobson and Bartholdt\ndebated the prohibition question be\nforo crowded galleries Underwood\nrose repeatedly to charge Mr. Hobson\nwbh misrepresenting him.\n\nGovernment ownership of telegraph\nand telephone lines is being serious\nly considered by the president. Con\nferences between the president and\nPostmaster General Burleson at Wash\nington have led to a gathering of in\nformatton about the practical work\nings of government ownership in other\ncountries.\n\nSecretary of War Garrison in his\nannual report said the time had not\nyet come for disarming or slackening\nIhe nations efforts for preparedness!\nin case of war. He also declared the\npresent provision for an army reserve\nis not working satisfactorily.\n\nA petition for national prohibition\nby constitutional amendment was\n{\u2022resented to President Wilson and\ncongress by a committee of 1.000.\n\nCounsel for Margaret Catherine Sul\nlivin, seventeen years old, obtained\nfrom the supreme court an order to\ncompromise lor $50,000 her claim j\nagainst the estate of Representative\nTimothy D. Sullivan, Tammany leader,\nit. bad not been known until this ac\ntion was taken that \u201cBig Tim\" had a\ndaughter.\n\nThe report of the house lobby inves\ntigating committee at Washington se-;\nrerely censures Representative Me- j\nDonald and asserts that the National\nAssociation of Manufacturers and oth- j\nt r organizations have maintained an I\nimproper lobby in Washington. It\ndoes not recommend or suggest any\naction by congress upon these find\nings.\n\npore President Wilson will spend\nhis Christmas vacation, if he takes\none. will be left to the \u201cMain House.\u201d\nThis is the president\u2019s way of saying\nMrs Wilson and the Misses Wilson\nwill make the selection\n\nDomestic\nWith its starboard main-shaft pro\npeller broken and several of its com\npartments flooded, the battleship Ver\nmont is on its way toward Hampton\ntoads on the return trip from the\nMediterranean cruise. It is under\nconvoy of the battleship Delaware and\nthe colliers Orion and Jason.\n\nThe Harvard seniors at Cambridge,\nMaes., have elected a negro, Alexan\nder L. Jackson of Englewood. N. J.,\ntheir orator for class day, 1914.\n\nJoseph Anderson was shot and\nkilled by Mamie Lindsey at Lan\ncaster. Pa. It is said that the dead\nman was jealous of his son. who\nhad eclipsed him in winning the af\nfections of the woman. She was ar\nrested.\n\nA bomb delivered in the office of\nthe O. K. Bottling company, 528-530\nWest Thirty-eighth strode New York,\nexploded and killed at sighteen-year\ncld girl, Ida Anusewitz. Thomas Mo\nra be, the office manager, was fatal,'.p\nhurt.\n\nDeath in the electric chair for Hans\nSchmidt, the renegade priest, whe\nconfessed the murder of Anna Aumul-\nIpr, was demanded b.y Assistant Dis\ntrict Attorney J. A. Delahanty, in his\nopening address to the jury in New\nYoik.\nj The motorcycle corps of the JN'uw\nYork police department of 23 men has\nj arrested more than 13,000 persons in\nI the last year. The total of fines im\nj posed lias been over $117,000.\n\nj Pere Marquette railroad was lined\ni $6,100 and the Wabash assessed S4OO\nby Judge Arthur J. Tuttel in the United\nStates court at Detroit, Mich., the for\nmer for failure to obey in full the fed\neral railroad laws, and the latter for\nthe violation of the safety appliance\nlaw.\n\nSheriff Smith of Bingham, Utah, re\nfused to grant the request of Mrs. W.\nS. Coo and Mrs. Alvida M. O. Cariz,\nwho asked that they be permitted to\nenter the Utah-Apex mine and try to\ninduce Ralph Lopez, Mexican desper\nado and slayer of six men, to surren\nder.\n\nAthur Schwichow is on his way\nfrom Nashville, Tenn., to Wheaton,\n111., to face a charge of murder for\nthe killing of Edmund Rotermund.\nassistant cashier of the Addison State\nbank. October 25. Cecil Baker, whose\nfriendship for Schwichow brought\nabout his arrest, has been held as an\naccessory.\n\nCharges that the American Tele\nphone and Telegraph company, the\nCentral Union Telephone company and\nthe Chicago Telephone company con\nspired to wreck the Interstate com\npany and drive it from the competing\nfield in Illinois, were made in a bill\nfiled in the circuit court on behalf of\n78 bondholders of the Interstate com\npany.\n\nAfter an all-night search Sheriff\nRussell captured three suspects for\nsafe blowing at Lawler, la. The men\nhad $l6O in money, many gold rings\nand a complete outfit of burglar t< ols.\n\nThe Safety and Sanitation confer\nence opened in New York and the\nspeakers said that while great strides\nhave been made in the last decade in\nthe direction of safety for shop work\ners, there is much yet to be done.\n\nMexican Revolt\nRead Admiral Fletcher, commander\nof the American naval forces in Mex\nican waters, ordered the rebels and\nfederals fighting at Tampico to cease\nfiring, threatening to open upon them\nwith the guns of the gunboat Wheel\ning if his order was not obey. BoHi\nsides obeyed.\n\nAmericans Avho arrived at El Paso\nTex., from Chihuahua reported that\nsince their occupation of that city the\nrebels had entered the British vice\nconsulate and forcibly seized Luis Ter\nrazas, Jr., a son of the wealthiest land\nowner in Mexico and placed him in\njail.\n\nThe Mexican congress nullified the\nrecent presidential election. New\nelections were called. In voting that\nthe presidential election of October\n26 was null the deputies decided to\nfix the first Sunday in July, 1914, as\nthe date for the new election. They\nalso confirmed the position of Huerta\nas provisional president until then.\n\nForeign\nThe Russian government proposer\nthe withdrawal of all foreign troops\nfrom Peking and the entire province\nof Chi-Li. China, including the lega\ntion guards, the regiments at Tientsin\nand the troops guarding the railway\nbetween the sea and Peking. Russia\nconsiders conditions in the north o!\nChina no longer dangerous to foreign\ners.\n\nA newspaper advertising campaign\nfor recruits to the British army is to\nbe undertaken in ail parts of Great\nBritain. The war office lias become\nconvinced of the value of the news\npapers as a medium.\n\n\u201cMoaa Lisa,\u201d Leonardo da Vinci\u2019s\nmasterpiece, the mysterious disap\npearance of which from the Louvre\nin August, 1911, threw the art world\ninto consternation, was found in Flor\nence, Italy. The man who stole it was\narrested.\n\nGreat excitement was caused on the\nbourse at Madrid. Spain, by the fail\nure of the Banko Hispano-Americano,\na $20,000,000 institution, to open its\ndoors.\nJohn Holloway, vice-chairman of\nthe port docks hoard, was shot during\na riot between nonunion coal men and\nstrikers at Dublin.\n\nLeon Letort, a well known French\naviator, was killed at Barbezieux. De\npartment of Charente, France. July\n14 Letort made a record nonstop\nflight of 590 miles from Paris to Ber\nlin In eight hours.\n\nMiss Helen Goudy of Chicago, noted\nbeauty of the American colony, be\ncame the bride of Lieut. Gerard Leigh\nof the First Life guards. The wed\nding took place in St. George\u2019s Han\nover square, London.\n\nThe city council of Paris, France, re\njected the proposal to restore sisters\nof charity and the members of other\nnursing orders to the posts they held\nin the Paris hospitals prior to tl-e sep\naraGon of church and state.\n\nPersonai\nWilliam As.or Chanler, African en\nplorer and author, i3 suffering in\nParis, France, from injuries sustained\nin an automobile accident ten days\nago. An operation on maa of ta.'r leg*\nwill fcn nneessar*\nSTATE GRANGE IN\nFAVORDF REFORMS\nWOMAN SUFFRAGE AND GOVERN\nMENT OWNERSHIP ARE\nADVOCATED.\nASK DIRECT VOTE AND RECALL\nImprovement of Income Tax Law and\nParcels Post Favored and\nGriffith Forestry Policy.\nCondemned.\nRhinelander. \u2014Nearly the entire\ncategory of political and economic re\nforms advocated in state and nation\nwere indorsed by resolutions adopted\nby the 100 delegates of the State\nGrange of Wisconsin in session here.\nResolutions were adopted favoring\ntiie principle of the referendum and\nrecall, improvement of the income tax\nlaw, woman suffrage, supervision of\nguarantee of bank deposits, extension\nof the system of county agriculiural\nrepicsentatives, government owner\nship, improvement in parcel post and\ndirect vote of people for presidential\nnominees.\nThe convention also favored a more\nliberal policy of the state in assisting\nnew settlers in clearing land and pro\ntested against what they called the\nGriffith policy of appropriating agri\ncultural lands for forestry purposes.\nAntigo was chosen as the next con\nvention city in 1914.\nFollowing are officers elected: Mas\nter, H. M. Culbertson, Medina; over\nseer, William Menning, Appleton; lec\nturer, Emma Wilde, Rhinelander;\nsteward, P. Gillette, Antigo; chaplain,\nA. C. Powers, Beloit; treasurer, Arthur\nKrause, Allenville; secretary, George\nH. Dawes, Tomahawk Lake; gate\nkeeper, E. K. Rick, Rhinelander;\nCeres, Mrs. Eva Howe, Antigo; Po\nmona, Mrs. Martha Bogenreif, Wash\nburn; Flora, Mrs. Susie Mclntosh,\nRhinelander; member executive com\nmittee, H. Howe, Antigo.\n$173,230 IN MOTOR LICENSES\nState Department Already Preparing\nFor Automobile Season\nof 1914.\nMadison. \u2014With the fiscal year near\ning an end, the issuing of licenses for\nauto vehicles and dealers in the office\nof Secretary of State Donald has prac\ntically closed. The record shows li\ncenses issued for the year, together\nwith the revenue derived, as follows:\nAutomobiles, 34,646 at $5 $173,230\nMotorcycles, 6,120 at $2 12,240\nDealers, 1,377 at $5 6,885\nDealers, 16 at $lO 160\nTotal $192,515\nOn Aug. 1, the la* tcreasing the\nfee for dealers from $5 to $lO went\ninto effect, which accounts for the two\nrates for that class. Auto licenses is\nsued in 1912 numbered 24,478, an in\ncrease of 10,068 for 1913.\nSecretary of State Donald is prepar\ning for the rush season of 1914. Al\nready over 100 applications have been\nreceived. The new number plates are\nto be in yellow background with em\nbossed white figures.\nLABOR MARKET DEPRESSED\nReports From Wisconsin's Free Em\nployment Bureaus Shows Supply\nGreatly Exceeds Demand.\nMadison. \u2014The depression in the la\nbor market noted in the reports of\nthe state free employment offices in\nOctober became more marked in No-*\nvember. For every 100 jobs there\nwere 145 applicants for employment\nduring this month. In October there\nwere only 107 and in November of\nlast year there were only 101 appli\ncants for every 100 jobs. The wom\nen\u2019s department of the employment of\nfices for the first time in several years\nshows a greater supply of labor than\ndemand.\nLong Hour Petitions Denied.\nMadison. \u2014The State Industrial com\nmission has originated a phrase to\nsupplant the trite command \u201cDo your\nshopping early\u201d The new phrase,\nslightly abridged, is \u201cthe petition is\ndenied\u201d With the advent of the\nChristmas season of 1913, the commis\nsion expected to receive scores of let\nters from tradesmen requesting per\nmission to employ women clerks\nlonger than the 10-hour limit. Con\ntrary to expectation, only three cities,\nAntigo, Kenosha and Superior, have\nasked such permission, and these pe\ntitions were denied.\nPriests Gather ist Green Bay.\nGreen Bay.\u2014Over 100 priests of the\nGreen Bay diocese assembled here in\nannual eucharistic conference at St.\nJoseph\u2019s orphanage. Bishop Fox pre\nsided at the conference.\nCo-operative Canning Company.\nLa Crosse. \u2014Farmers of La Crosse\ncounty have organized a co-operative\ncanning company capitalized at $50,-\n000. They will work along the line\nplanned at the recent meeting of the\nWisconsin Society of Equity.\nPlan Industrial Exposition.\nMarinette. \u2014The Marinette Develop\nment club will hold a manufacturers\u2019\nexposition here Feb. 25 and 26. All\nthe city's industries, cheese factories\ni aid cream eVies will be represented.\nLADYSMITH NEWS-BUDGET, LADYSMITH, WIS.\nINCOME TAX HEAVIEF\nAMOUNT TO BE COLLECTEO JliOO,\n000 MORE THAN LAST YEAR.\nCorporation Tax Greater in Spite o\nRate Reduction for Small Con\ncerns\u2014Six Counties Pay\nSIOO,OOO Each.\nMadison. \u2014individuals and corpora\ntions in the state will pay $4,091,090.\n30 income taxes this year. This is ai\nincrease of $601,739.14 over th<\namount of payments last year. Th\nstate tax commission in announcing\nthese figures claims that the increasj\nis due largely to greater prosperity ir\nthe state during the past year and t<\na better understanding of the law bj\nthe citizens. Of the total increase tc\nbe collected this yvur, $188,777.8!\nmore will be paid by individuals a:\ncompared with last year\u2019s collection:\nand $412,961.26 more come from cor\nporations.\nLast year the income tax coilectec\nfrom individuals in the seventy-on<\ncounties of the state aggregated\n$1,108,707.02, as compared with $1,297,\n484.90 to be collected this year. Tla\ncorporations paid $2,385,716.30 las\nyear, as compared with $3,494,423.31\nthis year. The largest single increase:\nare in Milwaukee county, where tin\ntotal income taxes collected last yea:\nwere $1,479,638.16 as compared wit!\n$1,825,024.15, an increase of $345,385.\n99. There are six counties in the stati\nwhere over SIOO,OOO will be coilectec\nin income taxes \u2014Milwaukee. Douglas\nDane, Kenosha, Racine and Winne\nbago. Each of these counties has\nlarge city within its borders, where the\nbulk of the tax is collected. Dane\ncounty will pay a total income tax this\nyear of $113,845.13; Douglas county\n$178,333.70; Kenosha, $149,238.79; Mil\nwaukee, $1,825,024.15; Racine, $223,\n195.62, and Winnebago. $114,378.17.\nThe entire expense of collecting\nthis tax of over $4,000,000 is paid bj\nthe state. It will cost the state abom\n3100,000 this year. The state receive:\n10 per cent of the tax collected, the\ncounty 20 per cent and the locality\nvhere the tax is returnable 70 pei\ncent. In spite of the reduction of the\ncorporation rate on small companies\nmade by the last legislature, the tota\namount of corporation tax to be co!\nlected shows a large\nIMPLEMENT DEALERS ELECT\nL. H. Waste of Seymour Chosen Presi\ndent at Closing Session of the\nState Association.\nMilwaukee.-\u2014The Wisconsin Retai\nImplement and Vehicle Dealers\u2019 assoc! i\nation closed its eighth annual meeting\nby the election of officers and the pass i\ning of resolutions, among them out\nmaking an indirect slap against Gov j\nMcGovern's marketing bill. New otti\ncers are:\nPresident\u2014L. H. Waite, Seymour.\nice President \u2014William Victoria\nMuscoda.\nDirectors\u2014Earl B. Robbins, Eau\nOiaire; T. J. Williams, Randolph, and\nJohn Du Bois, Green Bay.\nF. R. Sebenthali, Eau Claire, was!\ncontinued in the office of secretary.\nPASTOR VETERAN IS DEAD\nWilliam R. Brown. Former Chsplair\nof Wisconsin G. A. R., Passes\nAway at Age of 75.\nWaupaca.\u2014William R. Brown, 7i\nyears old, one of the best known mem\nbers of the Twenty-first Wisconsin I\nregiment, died here after an illness j\nof three months, in the hospital at j\nthe Wisconsin Veterans\u2019 home.\nWilliam R. Brown was chaplain ot I\nthe G. A. R. department of Wisconsin i\nat one time, having been elected\nunanimously at the Antigo convention\nin June, 1911. Prior to his coming\nhere, he was a Methodist minister\nhaving been stationed in various part?\nof Wisconsin.\nFormer Badger Educator Dead.\nMilwaukee.\u2014Dr. James Mac Alister,\nhead of schools of Milwaukee from\n1874 to 1881, later regent of Wiscon\nsin normal schools, <|!ied at sea on the\nsteamship Caribbean, bound from New\nYork to Bermuda, according to a wire\nless message. He resigned the presi\ndency of the Drexel institute at Phila\ndelphia last June because of ill health\nafter holding the office twenty years.\nAlleged Firebug Arrested.\nJanesville. \u2014Percy Merrell was ar\nrested for the alleged firing of a\nfreight car. He was recently refeased\nf ira an asylum to which he was com\nmitted after confessing to burning\nproperty worth $50,000.\nBurlington Banker Dead.\nBurlington.\u2014C. B. McCanna. presi\ndt?at of the Bank of Burlington and\nWisconsin Condensed Miik company,\ndied suddenly in New York, where he\nl Wat. on business.\nWhitewater Man Hangs Self.\nWhitewater. \u2014William McLane, aged\nj 36, city clerk for five years, committed\nj suicide by hanging himself. He hac\nj been in poor health for years. Wher\nfound he was still alive, but died poor\nafter.\ni\nEnds Life With Ac and.\n1\nI Madison. \u2014Walking into the roon\ni where his wife and little daughte\n*were sleeping, Lee Hungerford dr ini\ncarbolic acid and died. No cause wa\ngiven for the act.\nBIG SUIT BEGUN\nAGAINST STATE\nNORTHWESTERN INSURANCE CO.\nASKS RETURN OF TAX\nMONEY.\nSEEKS TO RECOVER MILLION\nComplaint Alleges Levy on Concern to\n8e Arbitrary and Exclusive, and\nThat Payment Was Brought\nAbout by Coercion.\nMadison.\u2014The Northwestern Mu\ntual Life Insurance company has be\ngun suit in the supreme court against\nthe state of Wisconsin to recover a\nsum exceeding $1,000,000, being the\namount paid, with interest, under\nprotest, as taxes for the years 1011\nand 1012.\nTiie interstate character of the\ncompany\u2019s business is set out in de\ntail in the complaint, which alleges\nthat of the total number of policies\nin force in the company more than\n90 per cent are on lives of people\nwho are not residents of Wisconsin*\nof the total insurance in force, more\nthan 02 per cent is outside of Wis\nconsin; of the total amount of real\nestate mortgage loans, more than 06\nper cent is on property outside of\nWisconsin; of the total amount of\noutstanding policy loans or advances\nmore than 98 per cent is outside of\nWisconsin; of the total payments in\n1511 and 1912 for death losses and\nendowments, the percentage exceed\ned 93; of the total gross receipts\nfrom ail sources in 1911 and 1912, it\nreached more than 93 per cent, and\nof the total premium receipts for\n1911 and 1912, more than 92 per\ncent were received from non-resi\ndents of Wisconsin.\nThe complaint further alleges that\nthe statutory classification for taxa\ntion is \u201carbitrary, discriminatory and\nunjust, and violates the rule that \u2018all\npersons subject to such legislation\nshall be treated alike\u2019 and that any\nclassification to be legal must be ra\ntional and founded upon real differ\nences in situation and conditions and\nin liabilities imposed\u201d; that payment\nif the taxes in question was made\nunder protest and threats to with\nhold the company\u2019s license to do any\nbusiness whatever and that the tax\nlaw in question is unconstitutional\nand void.\nThe complaint also alleges that\nproper claim was made against the\nstate for repayment of the taxes in\nquestion, bnt that the legislature of\n1918 disallowed the same.\nThe plaintiff asks judgment for the\nsum of -$987,836.4a, with interest on\n$482,193.23, the amount of the 1911\ntax, from Feb. 2 9, 1 12), and on\n$805,643.22, the amoixft of the 1912\ntax, from March 1, 1913.\nThe case will be placed for hear\ning on the January calendar of the\nsupreme court.\nCALLS BADGER LAW INVALID\nWestern Union Telegraph Company\nPressed Claim for Injunction to\nSave Wisconsin Charter.\nMadison. \u2014A brief lias been filed by\nthe Western Union Telegraph com\npany upon Atty. Gen. Owen setting\nforth arguments why the state should\nnot forfeit the corporation\u2019s Wiscon\nsin charter for having removed a state\ncase to the federal court. Verbay ar\nguments in the case were heard re\ncently before three federal judges in\nChicago and a decision is expected\nsoon.\nSupporting its request that the court\ngrant an injunction restraining the\nstate from cancelling the license, the\ncompany said: \u201cThe state of Wiscon\nsin may enact any law it deems wise\nand just to place foreign corporations\non an equity with domestic, provided\nonly no such law violates the supreme\nlaw of the land by depriving a for\neign corporation engaged in interstate\ncommerce or operating as a govern\nmental agency of its rights and priv\nileges. This the Wisconsin, act now\ncomplained of clearly does.\"\nThe state's counsel takes the ground!\nthat to decide the case in favor of the\ncompany would result in placing for\neign corporations on a better footing\nin this state than domestic corpora\ntions. Asa remedy for the condition\nwhich the state contends the company\nnow is in, it was suggested that the\ncompany may incorporate under the\ni; laws of Wisconsin.\nNational Trophy to Neenah Guard.\n1 Neenah. \u2014Word has been received\nhere that company I, First regiment\nW. N. G., has for the third consecu\ntive time won the national defense\ntrophy. This is a shooting trophy and\nthe highest attainable for marksman\nship.\nAbolish County Poor Farm.\nRhinelander.\u2014The Oneida county\nboard has voted to abolish the poor\nfarm, the outlying towns objecting to\nthe expense of caring for the inmates,\nnearly ail of whom come from this\ncity.\nMadison Sporting Man Injured.\nMadison. Ralph L. Richardson,\npresident of the Madison team of ihe\nillinois-Wisconsin Baseball league, sus\na'.ned a broken leg and othei serious\nniuries by being thrown from a buggy.\nMARKETS\nMilwaukee, Dec. 15, 1913.\nButter Creamery, extras, 32c;\nprints, 33c; firsts, 29@30c; seconds,\n25@27c; renovated. 26@26%c; dairy\nfancy, 28c.\nCheese- -American, full cream, new\nmade twins, 14% 15c; Young Am\nericas, 15@16%c; daisies, 14%@16c;\nlonghorns, 14%\u00ae15%c; limburger,\n13@13%c.\nEggs\u2014Current receipts fresh as to\nquality, 30@32c; recandled, extras, 35\n@37c; seconds, 19@21c.\nLive Poultry\u2014Fowls, 12 %c; roos\nters, #e; springers, 13c.\nWheat \u2014No. 1 northern, 92c; No. 2\nnorthern, S9c; No. 3 northern, 87c;\nNo. 1 velvet, 90c.\nCorn\u2014No. 3 yellow, 72c.\nOats\u2014No. 3 white, 41c; standard,\n41 41 %c.\nBarley\u2014No. 4, 56@60c; No. 3, 62\n@73c; Wisconsin, 58c.\nRye\u2014No. 2, 62@62%c.\nHogs\u2014Good heavy butchers, 7.80\u00ae\n7.90; fair to best light, 7.40\u00ae 7.80;\npackers, 7.40\u00ae 7.70.\nCattle\u2014Batchers\u2019 steers, 6.75@8.50;\nStockers and feeders, 5.25\u00ae7.00; cows,\nand heifers, 4.65@7.00; calves. 10.00\u00ae\n11.00.\nChicago, Dec. 16, 1913.\nCattle\u2014Beeves, 6.65\u00ae 9.70; Stockers\nand feeders, 4.80\u00ae 7.00; cows and heif\ners, 3.30\u00ae8.20; calves, $6.50@11.00.\nHogs\u2014Light, 7.30@7.85; heavy, 7.65\n@8.00; rough, 7.55\u00ae7.70; pigs, 5.50\u00ae\n7.40.\nMinneapolis, Dec. 15, 1913.\nWheat\u2014No. 1 hard, 8734 c; No. J\nnorthern, 87c; No. 2 northern. 85c.\nCorn \u2014No. 3 yellow, 68c.\nBarley\u201442\u00ae 62c.\nRye\u2014No. 2, 54\u00ae 57c.\nF1ax\u20141.41\u00ae1.45.\nNews Notes of Wisconsin.\nMadison. \u2014The school census of\nthe state, announced by State Super\nintendent C. P. Cary, shows there are\n772,304 children of school age in\nWisconsin. This is 3,169 less than\nthe number reported last year. The\nreduction is accounted for by the\ngreater accuracy of the reports du\nplications being almost entirely\navoided. Milwaukee county leads\nthe list with 138,688. Dane county\nis next with 23,0=44.\nMadison.\u2014The peddler has come\ninto his own. The Wisconsin su\npreme court, in sustaining the con\nstitutionality of the peddler\u2019s license\nlaw, defines the transient merchant\nas \u201cnot necessarily a \u2018deceitful fel\nlow\u2019 as described in Jacob\u2019s law\ndictionary. \u201cHe may be a very hon\norable man and yet be a peddler,\u201d\nsays Justice Marshall in the court\u2019s\nopinion.\nSuperior.\u2014Four University of\nWisconsin professors are among the\nrecent Douglas county \u201csettlers\u201d who\nare seeking to show the possibilities\nin agriculture in Northern Wiscon\nsin. The university faculty members\nare joint owners of 1,800 acres of\nDouglas county land several miles\nwest of Solon Springs.\nJanesville. \u2014With the idea of\neliminating useless giving to unwor\nthy families and systematizing the\ncharity work in this city during the\nholiday season, the Associated Chari\nties !i*is established a headquarters\nat the city hall and has named a spe\ncial committee to have charge of re\nceiving and distributing donations.\nBeloit.\u2014Plans have been com\npleted by the Beloit Federation of\nWomen for a municipal Christmas\ntree. The largest tree obtainable\nwill be erected in City park, lighted\nby electricity :nd appropriate ser\nvices, under the auspices of Beloit\nchurches, will be held on Christmas\neve. The tree will be lighted every\nnight during Christmas week.\nFond du Lac. \u2014Deputy. Warden\nRobert Bloedel of the state prison at\nWaupun, lias presented liis resigna\ntion to the state board of control and\nit becomes effective ou Dec. 31\u2019. It\nis understood that a difference of\nopinion with Warden Daniel Wood\nward regarding prison discipline\nprompted the step. Bloedel stated\nthat he would make a statement\nlati*r.\nMadison. \u2014The- architects- of Wis\nconsin are invited to enter a compe\ntition for plans- for the Wisconsin\nstate building, at the Sau Francisco\nexposition. The notice was issued by\nthe state exposition commission\nthrough Secretary D. E. Bo we Plans\nmust be: submitted by Dec. 23.\nNeenah. \u2014City Attorney Mott has\nbeen instructed to investigate and\nascertain if the 5 cent toll being\ncharged to Neenah and Appleton pa\ntrons when telephoning between\ncities is in accordance with the fran\nchise of the Bell Telephone company.\nAutigo.\u2014Dominick Fowler, a pio\nneer of this city, is dead, aged 77\nyears. He participated in the civil\nwar, and had the distinction of being\na member of one of the crews which\ncut the cables blocking the channel\nin the battle of Mobile bay.\nMadison. \u2014The supreme court\nholds that a person or company\nwhich has paid taxes under the in\ncome tax law cannot maintain a suit\nfor the recovery of those taxes or a\npart of them, but that the only re\ndress such a party has is through the\nstate legislature.\nMadison. \u2014With four new courses\nintroduced \u2014fencing, archery, appa\nratus work and sociat daneing\u2014en\nthusiasm runs high in the physical\neducation for women department of\nthe University of Wisconsin this year\nAll these courses are elective, but aL\nshow a good enrollment.\nifilSON OFFICER\nSLAIN jyiRGLAR\nWATCHMAN IS SHOT TO DEATH\nWHEN HE DISCOVERS SAFE\nBLOWER AT WORK.\nSI,OOO REWARD FOR ARREST\nAmerican Tobacco Company, Whose\nWarehouse Was Being Robbed,\nPosts Offer for Capture\u2014Shot\nGun Is Weapon Used.\nMadison \u2014John Longfield, watchman\nat the American Tobacco company\nwarehouse, was shot and killed by a\nburglar whom he found trying to open\nthe safe. The body was found the\nnext morning. A shotgun was used.\nLongfield, who leaves a family, has\nbeen employed as janitor of several\nbusiness blocks.\nGov. McGovern received a telegram\nfrom T. J. Maloney, president of the\nAmerican Tobacco company, offering\nSI,OOO reward for the capture of the\nburglars who shot and killed Long\nfield. It reads;\n\u201cGov. McGovern, Madison, Wis.: We\nauthorize you on behalf of the P. L.\nLorillard company, to offer a reward\nof SI,OOO for the capture and convic\ntion of the burglars who killed our\nnight watchman, John Longfield while\nin the faithful performance of his\nduty.\u201d\niKD;ANS DIVE FOR BODIES\nHalfbreed Experts Recover Body of\nOne of Three Girls Drowned in\nLake Geneva Last Summer.\nDelavan, \u2014Two halfblood Indians,\nJohn Jeremy and son of Stillwater,\nMinn., were successful after eight\ndays\u2019 work in finding the body of one\nof the three girls from Pella, la., who\nwere drowned in Lake Geneva last\nsummer.\nThese men came here fresh from\ntheir success in finding the bodies of\na father and son in Lake Mendota at\nMadison, Wis., after all others had\ngiven up the task. Should the experts\nbe successful in finding the other two\nbodies of the dead girls they will re\nceive a reward of SI,OOO.\nFew bodies of those drowned in\nLake Geneva are ever recovered, es\npecially if it occurs in deep water. In\nsome places the lake is more than\n300 feet deep and being fed almost\nwholly by spring water it is ice cold,\nthus preventing decomposition. The\nnames of the sisters drowned were\nDeguiese and the name of the other\nGezell. Many relatives of the two\ngirls from Pella, 1a.,, have been at\nWilliams Bay,. Wis., watching the\nwork.\nYOUTH BEST CORN GROWER\nHonor Awarded by University Ex\nperts for Yield of 133 Bushels,\n39 Pounds Per Acre.\nFond du Lac. \u2014Paul Koschnick, aged\n20, son of Mr. and Mrs. Charles Kos\nchniek, town of Eden, is champion\ncorn grower of Wisconsin, having\nsmashed all records with the yield\nof 133 bushels and thirty-nine pounds\nper acre. The former state record\nwas 133 bushels. Tile honor was\nawarded by Prof. G. P. Norgord and\nA. L. Stone of the state university at\nthe Fond du Lac, County Com and\nGrain show. record- was\ncertified by a committee which super\nvised the whole harvest.\nphysicians make a kick\nClaim Eugenic Examination Fee of\n$3.00, Provided by Law, la\nFar Toqj Low.\nRacine.\u2014Racine city and' county\nphysicians will refuse to act under the\nnew state eugenic marriage law, which:\nprovides that all' males must he ex\namined before marriage. The local;\nphysicians at a meeting of the County\nMedical society declared against ac\ncepting any appointments because the\nfee of $3 provided by law is too low-..\nThey claim the bare expense of tby\nte st totals more than $5. Dr. John ?>L\nBeffei, Milwaukee, said no self-respect\ning physician will act under the ear\ngenic law for the present fee.\nState Laws Protect Freshmen.\nMadison.\u2014Atty. Gen. Owen declared\nthat if any upper classman at the uni\nversity. forcibly ejected a freshman\nfrom a saloon, he would be guilty of\nassault and battery. \u201cTAditions\namount to nothing when it comes to\nenforcing them in the same sense as\nthe taws of the state,\u201d he said.\nWant New Government.\nWhitewater. \u2014A petition is being cir\nciliated asking for a vote on the com\nmission form of government.\nGrowers Hold Back Potatoes\nFond du Lac\u2014Four hundred and\nfifty empty potato cars were counted\non railroad tracks here in one day.\nThe condition resulted from a deter\nmination of Wisconsin growers not to\nship until prices advance.\nGreen Bay Man a Suicide.\nGreen Bay.\u2014Giving a child 5 cents\nto b#kak the news to his wife and\nchildren, Adolph Frederick, aged 60\nrears, committed suicide \\vy drb\\*fi\"-S\nacid at his flour mill.","height":"27561","width":"21822"}}
